The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, June 26, 2004 				 Andhra Paper to jack up capacity 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Hyderabad, June 25: Andhra Pradesh Paper Mills will raise production capacity at the Rajahmundry and Kadiam units to 1.97 lakh tonnes per annum from 1.53 lakh at a cost of Rs 554 crore.																								International Finance Corporation, the private sector funding arm of the World Bank, has sanctioned a loan of up to $35 million and equity participation of up to $5 million to part-finance the mill development plan, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today.																								The board has decided to borrow the $35-million offered by IFC. A plan to raise equity share capital is being worked out.Chairman L.N. Bangur said the expansion would improve technology, energy efficiency, marketability and ensure long-term environmental compliance. It will lead to a reduction in variable costs and improve sales realisations. The company will make pulp at Rajahmundry and paper at Kadiam, he added.																								The plan would be financed through term loans, debentures, equity and internal accruals. 																								The company has recently acquired the Andhra Pradesh governments 25.36 per cent stake, or 30 lakh shares, at Rs 130.95 per share.																								Executive director R. C. Mall said the project would be funded at an overall debt equity ratio of 1.25: 1. While around Rs 240 crore would be raised from internal accruals, the remaining Rs 310 crore will be raised from domestic financial institutions.																								In 2003-04, the company had exported 7,800 tonnes of paper valued at Rs 27 crore. Total income stood at Rs 450 crore, while net profit was Rs 23.36 crore. 
